	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>How Did They Do Music/GFX In The Old Days???</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Hello,<br /><br />I was wondering... How did great composers like Koji Kondo and Jun Ishikawa composed the tracks for the old games??? Did they have trackers??? Did they have MIDI-converting programs??? But each sound engine was on it's own mood!!! Maybe these sound composers had to transcript their scores to raw sound engine data, obligating them having programming knowledge??<br /><br />The same for graphics... How did they do???

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Shiru</b> [ Mon Jul 22, 2013 9:55 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: How Did They Do Music/GFX In The Old Days???</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Japanese composers seem to not like trackers concept, mostly used MML, and something MIDI-like later (PS1 era).<br /><br />As for graphics, in the early days everyone used paper sheets and manual convertion into data, then computers and converters were utilized to make the process easier and faster.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


